d fascism, this was an exceptionally turbulent time in the history of industrial capitalism as Taylorism and Fordism sought to increase production and consumption. This social landscape shaped modernist industrial novels. Key themes in these novels were class conflict, bad working conditions, worker alienation, changing workmen and employee cultures, urbanization, and worker migration. The primary goal was to document and publicize the real developments of working conditions in factories and offices, often aiming to influence both company welfare work and state social policies. This book focuses on the modernist industrial novel as written in five large industrial nations: the United States before WWII, the Stalinist Soviet Union, Weimar Germany, post-WWII Italy, and France.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aAmerican fictionxHistory and criticismy20th century. 0aEuropean fictionxHistory and criticismy20th century. 0aIndustries in literaturey20th century. 0aIndustries in literature. 0aLiterature and societyxHistoryy20th centuryzEurope. 0aLiterature and societyxHistoryy20th centuryzSoviet Union. 0aLiterature and societyxHistoryy20th centuryzUnited States. 0aLiterature and societyzEuropexHistoryy20th century. 0aLiterature and societyzSoviet UnionxHistoryy20th century. 0aLiterature and societyzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aRussian fictionxHistory and criticismy20th century. 0aWorking class in literaturey20th century. 0aWorking class in literature. 4aHistory. 4aLiterary Theory, Criticism, and History. 4aModern History. 4aSOC. 4aSocial and Political Sciences. 4aSociology and Social History. 7aHISTORY / Social History.2bisacsh  aModernist Industrial novels, industrial sociology, Americanization, worker alienation.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe G